SmarterEAT — quick deployment & run notes

Live endpoints
- Frontend: https://frontend-app.ashysea-0fd884f4.southeastasia.azurecontainerapps.io
- User API: https://user-app.ashysea-0fd884f4.southeastasia.azurecontainerapps.io/api
- Restaurant API: https://restaurant-app.ashysea-0fd884f4.southeastasia.azurecontainerapps.io/api
- Order API: https://order-app.ashysea-0fd884f4.southeastasia.azurecontainerapps.io/api
- Notification API: https://notification-app.ashysea-0fd884f4.southeastasia.azurecontainerapps.io/api

Run locally (Docker Compose)
1. Create per-service `.env` files inside each `services/<service-name>/` directory containing at minimum:
	- `MONGO_URI` (MongoDB Atlas or local Mongo)
	- `JWT_SECRET` (must be identical across services for auth to work)
2. Start services:
	```powershell
	docker compose up -d --build
	docker compose logs --tail 200
	```
3. Confirm services are healthy:
	- User health: `http(s)://localhost:1000/health`
	- Restaurant: `http(s)://localhost:4000/health`
	- Order: `http(s)://localhost:3000/health`
	- Notification: `http(s)://localhost:2000/health`

Notes for local setup
- The repository includes a template `.env` at root showing example connection strings — copy and edit to create real `.env` files per service.
- If you prefer local Mongo for development, add a `mongodb` service to `docker-compose.yml` and point `MONGO_URI` to `mongodb://mongodb:27017/<db>`.
- Services exit on DB connection failure by design; ensure `MONGO_URI` is reachable from Docker.

Azure deployment notes
- Container Registry: `smarteatregistry.azurecr.io` (images pushed here)
- Container Apps environment: `smarteat-env` in resource group `smarteat-rg` (Southeast Asia)
- Secrets configured in Container Apps: `mongo-uri` and `jwt-secret` (must match live Atlas creds and JWT secret)
- Frontend: container listens on port 5000 in the deployed image; Container App ingress was configured to `targetPort=5000`.
- Frontend runtime envs (`VITE_USER_SERVICE_URL`, `VITE_RESTAURANT_SERVICE_URL`, `VITE_ORDER_SERVICE_URL`, `VITE_NOTIFICATION_SERVICE_URL`) are set at Container App deploy time so the UI can call backend FQDNs.

Troubleshooting
- If frontend shows "stream timeout" or blank page, check Container App logs and confirm `targetPort` matches the port the container listens on, and that `VITE_*` envs are present.
- If JWT-protected endpoints return 401, verify the `JWT_SECRET` used by the client and services are identical.
- For Azure CLI issues (quoting, PowerShell parsing), use Azure Cloud Shell or pass sensitive values via `--registry-password` and `--secrets` when creating apps.

If you want, I can add a short script to rebuild and push frontend image and re-deploy the frontend Container App automatically.
